Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for the Fabrick Store project.

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics following the latest official documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- **File**: `package.json`
- **Action**: Added `@vercel/analytics` version ^2.0.1 to dependencies
- Installed using npm (matching the project's package manager)
- Updated `package-lock.json` to reflect the new dependency

### 2. Analytics Configuration
- **File**: `src/app/layout.tsx`
- **Actions**:
  - Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
  - Placed `<Analytics />` component at the end of the body element, after the ThemeProvider
  
### Implementation Details
The project uses Next.js 14.2.29 with the App Router architecture, so I followed the Next.js App Router-specific instructions from the official documentation:
- Imported Analytics from `@vercel/analytics/next` (Next.js-specific export)
- Added the component inside the body tag of the root layout
- Preserved all existing structure and styling

## Verification
✅ Build completed successfully - no errors or warnings
✅ Type checking passed during build
✅ Code linting passed during build process
✅ Lock files properly updated

## Next Steps
To enable analytics tracking in production:
1. Navigate to the Vercel dashboard for this project
2. Go to the Analytics section
3. Click "Enable" to activate the analytics routes (`/_vercel/insights/*`)
4. Deploy the application to Vercel
5. Analytics will begin tracking page views automatically once deployed

## Technical Notes
- The Analytics component is lightweight and only loads tracking scripts in production
- No configuration required in development mode
- Analytics data will be available in the Vercel dashboard after deployment
- Component is placed outside ThemeProvider to ensure it works independently
- Positioned at the end of body to avoid affecting page render performance
